The subject of this program is Robert Heinlein.

00:36.260 --> 00:41.820
Robert Heinlein to many readers is science fiction. His first story, Lifeline, was published in

00:41.820 --> 00:47.720
1939 by John W. Campbell. He was followed by several short stories, many reflecting Heinlein's

00:47.720 --> 00:54.140
themes of longevity, revolution, and mysticism. In 1947 he started a series of juvenile novels

00:54.140 --> 00:59.240
which have greatly shaped the way people perceive science fiction today. The turning point for

00:59.240 --> 01:06.140
Heinlein's work was the publication of Starship Troopers in 1959. This was followed by possibly

01:06.140 --> 01:11.160
the first science fiction bestseller, Stranger in a Strange Land. Heinlein's work became

01:11.160 --> 01:14.720
increasingly mystical and dominated by his own moral and ethical views.

01:15.760 --> 01:21.760
His early work, I think, is probably what most people today remember him for. As you said, his

01:21.760 --> 01:27.680
first story was published in 1939. And that story and the ones that followed it were really based

01:27.680 --> 01:33.580
on the old pulp formulas in a lot of ways. They were gimmick stories, some of them. They were

01:33.580 --> 01:38.320
adventure stories, exploration stories. They were all fast-moving, they were entertaining,

01:38.320 --> 01:47.120
they were clever. Lifeline, for instance, has as its gimmick a machine that predicts,

01:47.960 --> 01:53.880
not predicts, I'm sorry, it actually states the moment of a person's death. And a certain Dr.

01:54.060 --> 02:00.920
Panero demonstrates the validity or the efficacy of this machine and predicts people's death.

02:01.860 --> 02:07.360
Of course, the insurance companies don't like this too well, so they initiate certain plots to get

02:07.360 --> 02:12.840
rid of him. And near the end of the story, he's assassinated. In addition to being a gimmick

02:12.840 --> 02:21.040
story, it's also got a clever ending. Panero, it seems, had scanned his own lifeline with this

02:21.040 --> 02:26.940
machine and had foreseen his own death by the insurance company plot, but of course,

02:27.000 --> 02:31.000
wasn't able to do anything about it because the machine always told the truth.

02:32.380 --> 02:38.740
In the story, Rhodes must roll, Heinlein extrapolated a future transport system that was rather unique.

02:39.380 --> 02:46.020
It was a series of conveyor belts, if you will, that were placed side by side, each one being a

02:46.020 --> 02:51.440
faster speed than the next one. A person could step onto a very slow-moving five mile an hour belt

02:51.440 --> 02:57.180
and progress his way inward until he was traveling at quite a high speed. These things were huge.

02:57.180 --> 03:03.060
They stretched all over the country, and I suppose the world with people building buildings,

03:03.140 --> 03:07.260
businesses on the inner strips that would just move all the time.

03:08.220 --> 03:14.860
Rhodes must roll was written in 1940, and Heinlein was inaccurate in predicting that private cars

03:14.860 --> 03:20.300
would go out of use in the highways. But he was rather accurate in predicting that transportation

03:20.300 --> 03:25.040
would be fairly well watched over by large and powerful monopolies, which they are now.

03:25.720 --> 03:32.680
The crux of the book or the story is that it's a conflict between the union or the workers and

03:32.680 --> 03:39.160
management and what types of services the roads will have and inadequacies and pay and other

03:39.160 --> 03:45.200
things along that same line. Another one of his early stories and considered a classic

03:46.220 --> 03:52.740
for its theme is by his bootstraps, published in 1941. And this is a time travel story. Heinlein

03:52.740 --> 03:57.660
covered time travel at various times in his career. This, I believe, was his first, and some

03:57.660 --> 04:04.000
people consider a classic of the form. But it's a brain-twisting story. Of course, when you talk

04:04.000 --> 04:09.600
about time travel, you're dealing with all sorts of paradoxes. And what Heinlein does in this story

04:09.600 --> 04:18.780
is to construct a plot whereby the main character plays all the roles. He's a young man. He goes

04:18.780 --> 04:24.560
back in time. He meets himself as an old man. He's obviously gone back in time before.

04:26.780 --> 04:33.060
